<html>
<head>
	<title>Sudoku Game</title>
	<link href="/css/application.css" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css">
	<link href='http://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Amatic+SC' rel='stylesheet' type='text/css'>
	
</head>

<body>
	<div id="title">
	<h1>Life is too short for playing Sudoku </h1>
	</div>
  <div id="para">Sudoku (数独), originally called Number Place,[1] is a logic-based,[2][3] combinatorial[4] number-placement puzzle. The objective is to fill a 9×9 grid with digits so that each column, each row, and each of the nine 3×3 sub-grids that compose the grid (also called "boxes", "blocks", "regions", or "sub-squares") contains all of the digits from 1 to 9. The puzzle setter provides a partially completed grid, which typically has a unique solution.
Completed puzzles are always a type of Latin square with an additional constraint on the contents of individual regions. For example, the same single integer may not appear twice in the same 9×9 playing board row or column or in any of the nine 3×3 subregions of the 9×9 playing board.
</div>
	<div id="style"> <img src="/images/menstyle.png" />
	</div>
  <div id="flash">
    <%= flash[:notice] %>
  </div>
	

	<div id="sudoku">
		<form action="/" method="post">
  		<% 3.times do |row| %>
    		<div class='row'>
    			<% 3.times do |box| %>
      			<div class="box">
      				<% 3.times do |cell_row| %>
        				<div class="cell-row">
        					<% 3.times do |cell| %>
          					<%= partial :cell, :locals => {:cell_index => row * 27 + box * 3 + cell_row * 9 + cell} %>
      				    <%end%>
      				  </div>
      			  <%end%>
      			</div>
    		  <%end%>
    		</div>
	    <%end%>
      <button>CHECK</button>
    </form>
	</div>
  <form action="/new" method="get">
  <button id="button2">Get New</button>
</form>
<form action="/solution" method="get">
  <button id="button3">Solution</button>
</form>
</body>
</html>